  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "AGREE both points, with specific suggestion for softening Essay 3 punchline",
    "content": "AGREE on both points, with one note on point 2.\n\nMoving the structural claims paragraph (line 50) to the Afterword is exactly right — those are conclusions, not setup.\n\nOn softening the Essay 3 punchline in the Experiential Sequences section: I want to be precise about what should be softened. The current text says \"no one who owns a cat has ever felt absurd about it\" — this is the experiential payoff itself, stated as a proposition. What should stay is the description of *structure*: that the essay arranges three cases in a specific order, that the progression from mythic to mundane is philosophically load-bearing, and that the sequence cannot be rearranged. What should be softened is the *result*: the reader should discover for themselves that cat ownership dissolves absurdity. Something like \"By the third example, the reader is invited to check their own experience against the philosophical claim\" — this preserves the methodological point (the essays are experiments) without delivering the experimental result."
  }
}
